            . On the 8th of September I was in <placeName id="t18310908-399-crimeloc2055">Parliament-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-399-crimeloc2055" type="placeName" value="Parliament-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-399-crimeloc2055" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-399-off2053 t18310908-399-crimeloc2055"></join>, between ten and eleven o'clock, waiting for the procession; I did not feel this handkerchief taken - but it was held up, and I claimed it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CLARKSON. Q. You did not see it taken? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-399-person2854">
                  JAMES 
                  WILD
               <interp inst="t18310908-399-person2854" type="surname" value="WILD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-399-person2854" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-399-person2854" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was on duty on the day of the Coronation, and saw the prisoner with another man, attempting to pick several pockets, and at last he took this handkerchief from the prosecutor - he put it under his waistcoat; I told the prosecutor of it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined Q. Had you known him before? A. I cannot say I had; he did not come to me, produce the handkerchief, and say he had found it; I said it was a bad job for him - he never said a word; I was in plain clothes.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character, and a witness promised to take him into his employment.</p>
               <p>
